# SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Complete Code Derivation: A Full GET Request Workflow

This section walks through building a Flutter app that fetches a list of users from a public REST API (`https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users`). We will derive each step, from dependency installation to UI rendering.

### 3.1.1 Step 1 — Add Dependency to `pubspec.yaml`

The `http` package must be declared in the project's manifest file. Flutter uses **YAML (YAML Ain't Markup Language)** for configuration.

```yaml
dependencies:
  flutter:
    sdk: flutter
  http: ^1.2.0
```

**Logic Explanation:**
- The `http` package is fetched from `pub.dev` (Dart's package registry).
- The caret (`^`) operator means "compatible with version 1.2.0 up to but not including 2.0.0" — following **semantic versioning** rules.
- Run `flutter pub get` in the terminal to download the package.

### 3.1.2 Step 2 — Create the Data Model

A **Model class** encapsulates the structure of a single JSON object. This gives us **type safety** and IntelliSense in our IDE.

```dart
// lib/models/user.dart
class User {
  final int id;
  final String name;
  final String username;
  final String email;

  const User({
    required this.id,
    required this.name,
    required this.username,
    required this.email,
  });

  // Factory constructor: converts JSON Map → User object
  factory User.fromJson(Map<String, dynamic> json) {
    return User(
      id: json['id'] as int,
      name: json['name'] as String,
      username: json['username'] as String,
      email: json['email'] as String,
    );
  }

  // Serialization: User object → JSON Map
  Map<String, dynamic> toJson() {
    return {
      'id': id,
      'name': name,
      'username': username,
      'email': email,
    };
  }
}
```

**Logic Explanation:**
- `factory User.fromJson(...)` is a named factory constructor — Dart's idiomatic pattern for deserialization.
- The `as int` and `as String` are **type casts**; they will throw a `TypeError` if the JSON value is of the wrong type.
- `toJson()` is the inverse, used when sending data to the server.

### 3.1.3 Step 3 — Build the API Service Layer

The **service layer** abstracts network calls away from the UI. This is the **Single Responsibility Principle** in action.

```dart
// lib/services/api_service.dart
import 'dart:convert';
import 'package:http/http.dart' as http;
import '../models/user.dart';

class ApiService {
  // Base URL of the REST API
  static const String _baseUrl = 'https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com';

  // Fetches all users from the /users endpoint
  Future<List<User>> fetchUsers() async {
    // Step A: Build the URI
    final uri = Uri.parse('$_baseUrl/users');

    // Step B: Send the GET request
    final response = await http.get(uri);

    // Step C: Validate the response
    if (response.statusCode == 200) {
      // Step D: Decode the JSON body into a Dart List<Map>
      final List<dynamic> jsonList = jsonDecode(response.body);

      // Step E: Map each JSON object to a User model
      return jsonList
          .map((json) => User.fromJson(json as Map<String, dynamic>))
          .toList();
    } else {
      // Step F: Throw an exception for non-2xx responses
      throw Exception(
        'Failed to load users. Status: ${response.statusCode}',
      );
    }
  }

  // Creates a new user via POST
  Future<User> createUser(User user) async {
    final uri = Uri.parse('$_baseUrl/users');

    final response = await http.post(
      uri,
      headers: {
        'Content-Type': 'application/json; charset=UTF-8',
      },
      body: jsonEncode(user.toJson()),
    );

    if (response.statusCode == 201) {
      return User.fromJson(jsonDecode(response.body));
    } else {
      throw Exception('Failed to create user.');
    }
  }
}
```

**Logic Explanation of each step:**
- **Step A:** `Uri.parse()` converts the string URL into a `Uri` object, which the `http` package requires.
- **Step B:** `http.get()` returns a `Future<http.Response>`. The `await` keyword suspends execution until the future resolves.
- **Step C:** We always check `statusCode` before assuming success. A 200 OK means the request succeeded.
- **Step D:** `jsonDecode` is from `dart:convert` (Dart's standard library). It returns `dynamic` — either a `Map<String, dynamic>`, `List<dynamic>`, or scalar.
- **Step E:** `.map(...).toList()` transforms the raw list of JSON maps into a typed list of `User` objects.
- **Step F:** Throwing an `Exception` propagates the error up the call stack to the UI layer for handling.

### 3.1.4 Step 4 — Wire the UI with `FutureBuilder`

`FutureBuilder` is a Flutter widget that automatically rebuilds when a `Future` completes. It is the cleanest way to display async data.

```dart
// lib/screens/user_list_screen.dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import '../models/user.dart';
import '../services/api_service.dart';

class UserListScreen extends StatefulWidget {
  const UserListScreen({super.key});

  @override
  State<UserListScreen> createState() => _UserListScreenState();
}

class _UserListScreenState extends State<UserListScreen> {
  final ApiService _apiService = ApiService();
  late Future<List<User>> _usersFuture;

  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState();
    _usersFuture = _apiService.fetchUsers();
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: const Text('Users')),
      body: FutureBuilder<List<User>>(
        future: _usersFuture,
        builder: (context, snapshot) {
          // ConnectionState.waiting → show a loader
          if (snapshot.connectionState == ConnectionState.waiting) {
            return const Center(child: CircularProgressIndicator());
          }
          // hasError → show the error message
          else if (snapshot.hasError) {
            return Center(
              child: Text('Error: ${snapshot.error}'),
            );
          }
          // !hasData → empty state
          else if (!snapshot.hasData || snapshot.data!.isEmpty) {
            return const Center(child: Text('No users found.'));
          }
          // Success → render the list
          else {
            final users = snapshot.data!;
            return ListView.builder(
              itemCount: users.length,
              itemBuilder: (context, index) {
                final user = users[index];
                return ListTile(
                  leading: CircleAvatar(child: Text('${user.id}')),
                  title: Text(user.name),
                  subtitle: Text(user.email),
                );
              },
            );
          }
        },
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

**Logic Explanation:**
- `initState()` triggers the network call **once** when the widget is first inserted into the widget tree.
- `FutureBuilder` takes two required parameters: `future` (the async data source) and `builder` (a function that returns a Widget based on the `AsyncSnapshot`).
- The `AsyncSnapshot<T>` exposes four states: `connectionState`, `hasError`, `hasData`, and `data`.

## 3.2 Analytical Matrix: `FutureBuilder` States vs UI

| Snapshot State | Condition | UI to Render |
|---|---|---|
| `ConnectionState.waiting` | Future still pending | `CircularProgressIndicator()` |
| `snapshot.hasError` | Future threw an exception | Error message + retry button |
| `snapshot.hasData == false` | Future returned `null` or empty | "No data" placeholder |
| `ConnectionState.done` + `hasData` | Future completed successfully | Actual data widget tree |

## 3.3 Advanced: Using `dio` with Interceptors

For production apps, the `dio` package provides **interceptors** — middleware that runs before/after every request. They are essential for logging, authentication, and retry logic.

```dart
import 'package:dio/dio.dart';

final dio = Dio(BaseOptions(
  baseUrl: 'https://api.example.com',
  connectTimeout: const Duration(seconds: 5),
  receiveTimeout: const Duration(seconds: 3),
));

// Request interceptor: attach JWT to every request
dio.interceptors.add(InterceptorsWrapper(
  onRequest: (options, handler) {
    options.headers['Authorization'] = 'Bearer YOUR_TOKEN_HERE';
    print('➡️ ${options.method} ${options.uri}');
    return handler.next(options);
  },
  onError: (e, handler) {
    print('❌ ${e.message}');
    return handler.next(e);
  },
));
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Interceptor Logic Flow:** The `onRequest` callback modifies the outgoing `RequestOptions` (e.g., adds auth headers). The `onResponse` callback can transform the incoming response. The `onError` callback centralizes error logging and 401-token-refresh logic.

## 3.4 Error Handling Pattern (Production-Grade)

```dart
Future<List<User>> fetchUsers() async {
  try {
    final response = await http.get(Uri.parse(url));
    if (response.statusCode == 200) {
      return parseUsers(response.body);
    } else if (response.statusCode == 401) {
      throw AuthException('Token expired. Please log in again.');
    } else if (response.statusCode >= 500) {
      throw ServerException('Server error. Try again later.');
    } else {
      throw ClientException('Request failed: ${response.statusCode}');
    }
  } on SocketException {
    throw NetworkException('No internet connection.');
  } on TimeoutException {
    throw NetworkException('Request timed out.');
  } on FormatException {
    throw DataException('Invalid response format.');
  }
}
```

**Logic Explanation:**
- Specific exception types (`AuthException`, `ServerException`, `NetworkException`) let the UI display **context-aware error messages**.
- `SocketException` is thrown by `dart:io` when the device has no internet.
- `FormatException` is thrown by `jsonDecode` if the response body is not valid JSON.
- This is the **separation of concerns** principle: the service layer knows about HTTP, the UI knows about user experience.

## 3.5 Pull-to-Refresh Implementation

A common UX pattern is allowing users to swipe down to refresh data.

```dart
RefreshIndicator(
  onRefresh: () async {
    setState(() {
      _usersFuture = _apiService.fetchUsers(); // Re-trigger the future
    });
    await _usersFuture; // Wait for the new future to complete
  },
  child: FutureBuilder<List<User>>(...)
)
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Why re-assign the `Future`?** `FutureBuilder` only listens to the `Future` object passed to it. To trigger a rebuild, you must assign a **new** `Future` instance and call `setState` so the widget rebuilds with the new future.

<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

