# SECTION 5: KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question 1 (3 Marks)
**[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023, Model Paper]**

**Q: Differentiate between `Future`, `async`, and `await` keywords in Dart. Why are they essential for network calls in Flutter?**

**Model Answer:**

| Keyword | Type | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `Future<T>` | A class (type) | Represents a value that will be available **later** (asynchronous result) |
| `async` | Modifier keyword | Marks a function as asynchronous; it automatically returns a `Future` |
| `await` | Operator keyword | Pauses execution of the current async function until the awaited `Future` completes |

**Why essential for network calls:** HTTP requests are time-consuming (hundreds of ms to seconds). Since Dart runs on a **single-threaded event loop**, blocking the thread would freeze the UI. `async`/`await` allows the network call to run in the background while the UI continues rendering at 60 FPS. When the response arrives, Dart schedules a microtask to resume the function, and the UI is updated via `setState` or `FutureBuilder`.

---

### Question 2 (3 Marks)
**[KTU University Exam - June 2024, Model Paper]**

**Q: What is JSON? Explain the role of `jsonEncode()` and `jsonDecode()` in Flutter with a small example.**

**Model Answer:**

**JSON (JavaScript Object Notation)** is a lightweight, text-based, language-independent data interchange format. It uses key-value pairs (objects) and ordered lists (arrays). It is the **de facto standard** for REST API communication.

- `jsonEncode(dartObject)`: Serializes a Dart `Map` or `List` into a JSON-formatted `String`. Used when sending data in a `POST`/`PUT` request body.
- `jsonDecode(jsonString)`: Deserializes a JSON-formatted `String` into a Dart `Map<String, dynamic>` or `List<dynamic>`. Used when reading the response body.

**Example:**
```dart
import 'dart:convert';

void main() {
  // Dart Map → JSON String (Encoding)
  Map<String, dynamic> user = {'name': 'Alice', 'age': 25};
  String jsonStr = jsonEncode(user);
  print(jsonStr); // {"name":"Alice","age":25}

  // JSON String → Dart Map (Decoding)
  Map<String, dynamic> parsed = jsonDecode(jsonStr);
  print(parsed['name']); // Alice
}
```

---

## 5.2 Part B Questions (14 Marks Each)

### Question A (14 Marks)

**[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023, Model Paper]**

**Q (a)** Explain the steps to make an HTTP GET request in Flutter using the `http` package to fetch a list of users from a REST API. Provide a complete code example. **(7 Marks)**

**Q (b)** What is the role of a Model class in Flutter networking? Design a `Product` model class with `fromJson()` and `toJson()` methods for the following JSON structure:
```json
