## 3.3 Case Study 3: Implementing Hive in Flutter

**Scenario:** A to-do app must store user tasks (complex objects) with near-instantaneous retrieval.

### Step 1: Add Dependencies

```yaml
dependencies:
  hive: ^2.2.3
  hive_flutter: ^1.1.0

dev_dependencies:
  hive_generator: ^2.0.1
  build_runner: ^2.4.13
```

> [!NOTE]
> `hive_generator` and `build_runner` are **dev dependencies** because they are only used during code generation (analogous to a compiler toolchain).

### Step 2: Define the Model with TypeAdapter

```dart
import 'package:hive/hive.dart';

part 'task.g.dart';  // Generated file

@HiveType(typeId: 0)  // typeId must be unique across the app
class Task extends HiveObject {
  @HiveField(0)
  String title;

  @HiveField(1)
  bool isCompleted;

  @HiveField(2)
  DateTime createdAt;

  Task({required this.title, this.isCompleted = false, DateTime? createdAt})
      : createdAt = createdAt ?? DateTime.now();
}
```

**Why `@HiveField` annotations?**
Each field gets a unique numeric ID. This is essential for **forward and backward compatibility** — when you add new fields in a later version, old data can still be read because the IDs remain stable.

### Step 3: Run Code Generation

```bash
flutter pub run build_runner build
```

This produces `task.g.dart` containing the boilerplate `TaskAdapter` class.

### Step 4: Initialize Hive and Open Box

```dart
import 'package:hive_flutter/hive_flutter.dart';

class HiveService {
  static const String taskBoxName = 'tasks';

  static Future<void> init() async {
    await Hive.initFlutter();  // Initializes Hive for Flutter (handles path)
    Hive.registerAdapter(TaskAdapter());  // Register custom adapter
    await Hive.openBox<Task>(taskBoxName);  // Open the box
  }

  // --- CREATE / UPDATE ---
  static Future<void> addTask(Task task) async {
    final box = Hive.box<Task>(taskBoxName);
    await box.put(task.title, task);  // Key = title, Value = Task object
  }

  // --- READ ---
  static Task? getTask(String title) {
    return Hive.box<Task>(taskBoxName).get(title);
  }

  static List<Task> getAllTasks() {
    return Hive.box<Task>(taskBoxName).values.toList();
  }

  // --- DELETE ---
  static Future<void> deleteTask(String title) async {
    await Hive.box<Task>(taskBoxName).delete(title);
  }
}
```

### Step 5: Encryption in Hive (Bonus High-Yield Topic)

```dart
// Generate a 32-byte secure key
final encryptionKey = await Hive.generateEncryptionKey();

// Open an encrypted box
await Hive.openBox('secureBox',
  encryptionCipher: HiveAesCipher(encryptionKey)
);
```

> [!WARNING]
> **Exam Pitfall:** If you lose the encryption key, the data is **permanently inaccessible**. There is no backdoor. This is a deliberate security feature.

