## 3.4 The Performance Triad — A Mathematical Comparison

To quantify the performance differences, consider **n = 10,000 records**:

$$\text{Lookup Time}_{\text{SharedPrefs}} = O(n) \quad \text{(linear scan of XML)}$$

$$\text{Lookup Time}_{\text{SQLite}} = O(\log n) \quad \text{(B-Tree index)}$$

$$\text{Lookup Time}_{\text{Hive}} = O(1) \quad \text{(hash map)}$$

For **n = 10,000**:

$$\text{SharedPrefs}_{\text{avg}} \approx 10,000 \cdot \mu_{\text{read}}$$

$$\text{SQLite}_{\text{avg}} \approx \log_2(10,000) \cdot \mu_{\text{btree}} \approx 13 \cdot \mu_{\text{btree}}$$

$$\text{Hive}_{\text{avg}} \approx 1 \cdot \mu_{\text{hash}}$$

Where $\mu_{\text{read}}$, $\mu_{\text{btree}}$, and $\mu_{\text{hash}}$ are the per-operation disk I/O latencies.

> [!NOTE]
> **Caveat:** The above assumes a key-based direct lookup. SharedPreferences *also* has O(1) lookup *if the key is known*. The O(n) is for retrieving *all entries* or searching by value. This is a common viva clarification.
