### 📌 Question B (Choice 2) — 14 Marks

> **[KTU University Exam — Model Paper 2024 Scheme, Module 3]**

**(a)** Compare SQLite and Hive in Flutter. Mention at least four comparison points and explain when to prefer Hive over SQLite with a real-world scenario. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Design and implement a Flutter application using **Hive** to store a list of `Task` objects where each task has `id`, `title`, `isCompleted`, and `createdAt` fields. Show the model class with `@HiveType` annotations and all CRUD operations. **(7 marks)**

#### Model Solution for (a):

**Comparison: SQLite vs Hive**

| Comparison Point | SQLite | Hive |
|---|---|---|
| **Language Foundation** | Uses SQL (declarative) | Uses Dart method calls (imperative) |
| **Native Dependencies** | Requires C library (native code) | Pure Dart — no native code |
| **Cross-Platform Support** | Mobile and Desktop only | Mobile, Web, and Desktop |
| **Schema Management** | Schema is mandatory (CREATE TABLE) | Schema-less — flexible structure |
| **Query Capability** | Full SQL: JOIN, GROUP BY, subqueries | Limited — iteration over box values |
| **Performance for Object Storage** | Requires ORM mapping | Direct object storage |
| **Encryption** | Requires third-party SQLCipher | Built-in AES-256 |

**When to Prefer Hive Over SQLite — Real-World Scenario:**

**Scenario:** A **fitness tracking app** that stores thousands of workout sessions locally. Each session is a complex Dart object with nested maps (e.g., exercise sets, reps, weights, timestamps).

**Why Hive is preferred:**
1. **No SQL overhead:** The data is non-relational — we never need to JOIN workout sessions with user profiles.
2. **Faster read/write:** Direct object storage means no `Map` conversion is needed.
3. **Works on Flutter Web:** The same codebase runs on web browsers, where SQLite has limited support.
4. **Schema flexibility:** New fields (e.g., `heartRate`) can be added without database migrations.
5. **Built-in encryption:** Health data is sensitive; Hive's AES-256 encryption is straightforward to enable.

**When SQLite is still preferred:** If the app later needs analytics like "average reps per muscle group" with complex aggregations, SQLite's `GROUP BY` and `AVG()` functions are far more efficient than iterating through Hive boxes.

*(Mark Distribution: 3 marks for comparison points, 2 marks for scenario, 2 marks for justified reasoning.)*

#### Model Solution for (b):

**Complete Hive Implementation for Task Manager:**

**Step 1: Define the Model (`task.dart`):**

```dart
import 'package:hive/hive.dart';
part 'task.g.dart';

@HiveType(typeId: 1)
class Task extends HiveObject {
  @HiveField(0)
  String id;

  @HiveField(1)
  String title;

  @HiveField(2)
  bool isCompleted;

  @HiveField(3)
  DateTime createdAt;

  Task({
    required this.id,
    required this.title,
    this.isCompleted = false,
    DateTime? createdAt,
  }) : createdAt = createdAt ?? DateTime.now();
}
```

**Step 2: Generate the Adapter:**
Run: `flutter pub run build_runner build --delete-conflicting-outputs`

This produces `task.g.dart` automatically.

**Step 3: Initialize and CRUD Operations (`task_repository.dart`):**

```dart
import 'package:hive_flutter/hive_flutter.dart';
import 'task.dart';

class TaskRepository {
  static const String boxName = 'tasks_box';
  late Box<Task> _box;

  // Initialize Hive and open the box
  Future<void> init() async {
    await Hive.initFlutter();
    if (!Hive.isAdapterRegistered(1)) {
      Hive.registerAdapter(TaskAdapter());
    }
    _box = await Hive.openBox<Task>(boxName);
  }

  // CREATE — Add a new task
  Future<void> addTask(Task task) async {
    await _box.put(task.id, task);
  }

  // READ — Get a task by ID
  Task? getTask(String id) {
    return _box.get(id);
  }

  // READ — Get all tasks sorted by creation date
  List<Task> getAllTasks() {
    final tasks = _box.values.toList();
    tasks.sort((a, b) => b.createdAt.compareTo(a.createdAt));
    return tasks;
  }

  // UPDATE — Modify a task (toggle completion)
  Future<void> toggleTaskCompletion(String id) async {
    final task = _box.get(id);
    if (task != null) {
      task.isCompleted = !task.isCompleted;
      await task.save();  // HiveObject provides built-in save()
    }
  }

  // DELETE — Remove a task
  Future<void> deleteTask(String id) async {
    await _box.delete(id);
  }

  // DELETE ALL — Clear the box
  Future<void> clearAll() async {
    await _box.clear();
  }

  // Close the box (call on app disposal)
  Future<void> close() async {
    await _box.close();
  }
}
```

**Step 4: Main Entry Point (`main.dart`):**

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'task_repository.dart';
import 'task.dart';

void main() async {
  WidgetsFlutterBinding.ensureInitialized();
  final repo = TaskRepository();
  await repo.init();
  runApp(MyApp(repository: repo));
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  final TaskRepository repository;
  const MyApp({super.key, required this.repository});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      home: TaskListScreen(repository: repository),
    );
  }
}

class TaskListScreen extends StatefulWidget {
  final TaskRepository repository;
  const TaskListScreen({super.key, required this.repository});
  @override
  State<TaskListScreen> createState() => _TaskListScreenState();
}

class _TaskListScreenState extends State<TaskListScreen> {
  void _addSampleTask() {
    final task = Task(
      id: DateTime.now().millisecondsSinceEpoch.toString(),
      title: 'New Task ${DateTime.now().second}',
    );
    widget.repository.addTask(task);
    setState(() {});
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    final tasks = widget.repository.getAllTasks();
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: const Text('Hive Task Manager')),
      body: ListView.builder(
        itemCount: tasks.length,
        itemBuilder: (context, index) {
          final task = tasks[index];
          return ListTile(
            title: Text(
              task.title,
              style: TextStyle(
                decoration: task.isCompleted
                    ? TextDecoration.lineThrough
                    : TextDecoration.none,
              ),
            ),
            subtitle: Text(task.createdAt.toString()),
            leading: Checkbox(
              value: task.isCompleted,
              onChanged: (_) async {
                await widget.repository.toggleTaskCompletion(task.id);
                setState(() {});
              },
            ),
            trailing: IconButton(
              icon: const Icon(Icons.delete),
              onPressed: () async {
                await widget.repository.deleteTask(task.id);
                setState(() {});
              },
            ),
          );
        },
      ),
      floatingActionButton: FloatingActionButton(
        onPressed: _addSampleTask,
        child: const Icon(Icons.add),
      ),
    );
  }
}
